Obscurity zones.

An obscurity zone is a rectangular area on the map that hides certain entity types from the player's senses while they are standing inside it. Unlike the character blocker, which disables the spier or info menu outright, an obscurity zone leaves both systems running and just filters out the chosen entity types so the world feels harder to perceive without losing access to those features.

Each obscurity zone has a minimum and maximum x and y for its bounds (plus a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), a list of which player-facing systems it affects, a list of entity types it hides or shows, and a whitelist toggle. On 3d maps the zone only applies while the player's z is also inside the zone's z range; on 2d and topdown maps the z gate is bypassed.

Affected systems.

A zone can affect either the spier, the object info menu, or both. The build form has a checkable list with two options:

spier: When checked, the zone filters entries out of the spire reports while the player stands inside the zone. Scanning toward an obscured entity behaves as if that entity is not on the map.
info menu: When checked, the zone filters entries out of the object info menu while the player stands inside the zone. Hidden entities don't appear in the list and are not counted in the total objects header. If every entity is hidden, opening the menu speaks there are no objects on the field to view. and bails out instead of opening an empty menu.

You can check one, the other, or both. The same zone can apply identical rules to both systems without needing to define two overlapping zones.

Entity types.

The build form has a checkable list of every entity type the spier and info menu can report. The available types are:

aircraft, bike, blockage, calendar, checkpoint, clock, conveyor belt, door, elevator, fire, floor breaker, force field, hazard, item, lift, mine, npc, passage, platform, projectile, safe zone, security camera, sign, spike, staircase, switch, teleporter, time bomb, travelpoint, vehicle, wall.

You must tick at least one entity type for the zone to be valid.

Blacklist and whitelist.

Obscurity zones can operate in blacklist and whitelist modes, set by the Enable whitelist checkbox at the bottom of the form.

Blacklist (false): Only the listed entity types are hidden. Everything else stays visible.
Whitelist (true): Only the listed entity types are shown. Everything else is hidden.

So a blacklist zone with door and wall ticked hides doors and walls and shows everything else, while a whitelist zone with the same selection shows only doors and walls and hides everything else.

Position dependence.

Obscurity zones are local. Their effect only applies while the player is standing inside the zone's bounds. Walking out restores the full unfiltered view immediately. This makes it possible to design hallways where the spier goes quiet on traps, rooms where the info menu only lists npcs, or any other localized restriction without disabling spying or the info menu globally.

Overlapping zones.

If multiple obscurity zones overlap and the player is inside more than one at the same time, an entity is hidden if any of the active zones marks it as hidden. So overlapping zones combine their hide rules; an entity stays visible only when none of the active zones hide it.
